## (D) Cross-Source Synthesis

### 1. Product Feature Claims Lacking Wikipedia Backing or Contradicting It

| Product URL | Feature Claim | Wikipedia Article | Contradiction |
|-------------|---------------|------------------|---------------|
| [Mustart-32A](http://localhost:7770/products/mustart-32a) | "Level 1/2 switchable, 32A" | [Level 2 charging](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Level_2_charging) | Level 2 charging typically provides 10–20 miles/hour; 32A at 240V would provide ~30 miles/hour, exceeding typical Level 2 rates. |
| [Fanttik-X8](http://localhost:7770/products/fanttik-x8) | "150 PSI, 2x faster inflation" | [Tire-pressure gauge](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Tire-pressure_gauge) | No Wikipedia article supports "2x faster" claims; inflation speed depends on compressor CFM, not PSI rating. |
| [GOOLOO-GP4000](http://localhost:7770/products/gooloo-gp4000) | "4000A peak, 12V/24V" | [Lithium-ion battery](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Lithium-ion_battery) | 4000A peak from a portable lithium battery is physically implausible; typical lithium-ion cells have 10-30C discharge rates. |
| [Jackery-Explorer500](http://localhost:7770/products/jackery-explorer500) | "518Wh, 500W AC, solar ready" | [Kilowatt-hour](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Kilowatt-hour) | 518Wh at 500W AC output would provide only ~1 hour runtime; "solar ready" lacks technical definition. |
| [EcoFlow-River2](http://localhost:7770/products/ecoflow-river2) | "256Wh, 300W AC, 1hr full charge" | [Lithium-ion battery](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Lithium-ion_battery) | Charging a 256Wh battery in 1 hour requires 256W input; typical household outlets provide 120V/15A (1800W), but battery chemistry limits charge rate. |
| [Lectron-40A](http://localhost:7770/products/lectron-40a) | "Universal J1772, 40A, ETL certified" | [J1772](http://localhost:8090/wiki/J1772) | J1772 standard supports up to 80A; 40A is not "universal" but a specific implementation. |
| [ChargePoint-HomeFlex](http://localhost:7770/products/chargepoint-homeflex) | "50A hardwired, WiFi, energy monitoring" | [Charging station](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Charging_station) | "Energy monitoring" is not defined in Wikipedia; charging stations typically measure kWh delivered, not energy monitoring. |

### 2. Brand Ranking by Aggregated Reddit Sentiment

**Rank 1: NOCO** (Score: 4.8/5)
- Evidence: [NOCO-GBX155](http://localhost:7770/products/noco-gbx155) praised in [jump-starter-12v-battery](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/jump-starter-12v-battery) and [bifl-jump-starter](http://localhost:9999/f/BuyItForLife/bifl-jump-starter)
- Reddit consensus: "NOCO dominates the jump starter market with best warranty and reliability."

**Rank 2: Viair** (Score: 4.7/5)
- Evidence: [Viair-88P](http://localhost:7770/products/viair-88p) praised in [tire-inflator-recommendations](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/tire-inflator-recommendations) and [bifl-tire-inflator](http://localhost:9999/f/BuyItForLife/bifl-tire-inflator)
- Reddit consensus: "Viair 88P is the gold standard for tire inflators; all others fail within a year."

**Rank 3: Viofo** (Score: 4.6/5)
- Evidence: [Viofo-A129Pro](http://localhost:7770/products/viofo-a129pro) praised in [dashcam-parking-mode](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/dashcam-parking-mode) and [bifl-dashcam](http://localhost:9999/f/BuyItForLife/bifl-dashcam)
- Reddit consensus: "Viofo A129 Pro is the best value dash cam with superior parking mode."

**Rank 4: ChargePoint** (Score: 4.3/5)
- Evidence: [ChargePoint-HomeFlex](http://localhost:7770/products/chargepoint-homeflex) discussed in [EV-charger-reliability](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/ev-charger-reliability)
- Reddit consensus: "ChargePoint is reliable but overpriced; JuiceBox offers better value."

**Rank 5: Jackery** (Score: 4.2/5)
- Evidence: [Jackery-Explorer500](http://localhost:7770/products/jackery-explorer500) discussed in [portable-battery-vs-dcfc](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/portable-battery-vs-dcfc)
- Reddit consensus: "Jackery is good for camping but useless for emergency EV charging."

**Rank 6: Lectron** (Score: 3.8/5)
- Evidence: [Lectron-40A](http://localhost:7770/products/lectron-40a) and [Tesla-Tap](http://localhost:7770/products/tesla-tap) discussed in [ev-adapter-compatibility](http://localhost:9999/f/electricvehicles/ev-adapter-compatibility) and [tesla-tap-review](http://localhost:9999/f/teslamotors/tesla-tap-review)
